There are 3 access specifiers in c++ OOPs
(i)Public-Can be accessed from anywhere outside the class.
(ii)Private-Can not be accessed outside the class.
(iii)Protected-Used in inheritance
private

Anything declared inside private: can only be accessed by the class itself.

Example:

class BankAccount
{
private:
    int balance;
};

Now in main():

BankAccount acc;

acc.balance = 100;

❌ Error!

Because balance is private.

public

Anything inside public: can be accessed from anywhere.

Example

class BankAccount
{
public:
    string owner;
};

Now

BankAccount acc;

acc.owner = "Ishan";

cout << acc.owner;

Output

Ishan

Works perfectly.

Why do we hide data?

Suppose balance is public.

class BankAccount
{
public:
    int balance;
};

Now someone can do

BankAccount acc;

acc.balance = -500000;

Now the account has negative money.

That makes no sense.

Instead

class BankAccount
{
private:
    int balance;
};

Only the class itself can change it.

The user must request:

Deposit 500
Withdraw 200

The class decides if that's allowed.

This concept is called encapsulation—keeping data safe by controlling access.

Example
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Student
{
public:
    string name;

private:
    int marks;
};

int main()
{
    Student s;

    s.name = "Ishan";

    cout << s.name << endl;

    s.marks = 95;
}

Error:

'marks' is private within this context

because

private:
    int marks;

cannot be accessed outside the class.
